In article <strnlghtCG5zF2.6Kp@netcom.com>, strnlght@netcom.com (David Sternlight) writes:
> In an earlier message in this newsgroup I promised to report what RSADSI/PKP
> said about the idea of buying Viacrypt PGP (DOS version) and then using the
> unlicensed Mac version of PGP (if one had a Mac  but not a DOS machine).
> 
> The answer, in brief, is no. Quoting from the response:
> 
> "Our position is simple: Products are licensed, or they're not. (It is
> the right of the patent holder to grant licenses or not grant them.
> Having paid a royalty for one product does not legitimize a
> non-licensed product, however similar.) 
> 
> "The non-Viacrypt pgp software is NOT licensed, and therefore, in our
> view, clearly infringes.  There are several other legal issues
> regarding the Viacrypt situation, but I'm not at liberty to discuss
> those.
> 
> "We have no current plans to offer patent licenses to infringing
> products that exist unlicensed.  A license is required to make, use,
> or sell any patented device. We insist on licensing those who wish to
> do any of the above."
> 
> No flames, please--I'm only the messenger here.
> 
> Let's not start another argument about the above. It's their position, o.k.,
> and one may agree or disagree with it, but that won't alter that it's their
> position in the matter.
> 
> This message is intended to be informational, and not to start yet another
> round of argumentation about this. It is about their position on the matter,
> not "the truth."
> 
> David
> 
> 
> -- 
> David Sternlight         When the mouse laughs at the cat,
>                          there is a hole nearby.--Nigerian Proverb
